In this section, we describe the high-level approach of RAIFLE, our reconstruction attack on IFL.
Descriptions of useful notations used throughout the subsequent sections are provided in Table 1.
Convergence analysis of RAIFLE is provided in Appendix A, and specific implementation details can be found in Appendix B.

For OLTR, we used the LETOR 4.0 dataset and the MSLR dataset (Qin and Liu, 2013), specifically the training set of the first fold of MQ2007 in LETOR and MSLR-WEB10K in MSLR.
(Note that we primarily report results for the MSLR dataset as it has much more data and the results are similar.)
For RS, we used the MovieLens-100K dataset (Harper and Konstan, 2015).
The only preprocessing done was normalizing the features in MSLR and binarizing the interactions in MovieLens (e.g. 1 if interacted, 0 if not).
All of our interactions are binary.
We simulated the user clicks for OLTR using the “navigational” and “information” click chain model following previous work on federated OLTR (Kharitonov, 2019; Wang et al., 2021).
With regards to RS, for each user, we sampled non-interacted items with a ratio of 4:1 to interacted ones. Some statistics on the data are provided in Table 2.

references:
One of the earliest and most influential RS algorithms is collaborative filtering (CF), which recommends items based on the behaviors and preferences of similar users (Goldberg et al., 1992).
A common approach to CF is matrix factorization (Canny, 2002): essentially, the user-item interaction matrix is factored into two lower-dimensional latent factor matrices, one for the user embeddings and one for the item embeddings.
Building upon CF, federated collaborative filtering (FCF) formulates the item matrix as public parameters (i.e., known by all participants) and the user matrix as private parameters, which are privately updated by each user without being shared with anyone else (Ammad-ud-din et al., 2019).
This idea has been incorporated in various subsequent works such as federated neural collaborative filtering (FNCF) (Perifanis and Efraimidis, 2022) and federated graph neural net for recommendation (FedGNN) (Wu et al., 2022).
Keeping user embeddings private by itself does not automatically guarantee privacy for users since their interactions can be inferred through multiple observations of unprotected updates (Chai et al., 2021) or through RAIFLE (Table 3).

RAIFLE’s performance for RS is shown in Table 3.
For FCF, jointly estimating interactions and user embeddings leads to a strong AUC of ≈0.98absent0.98\approx 0.98, while the original RAIFLE is no better than random guessing.
Furthermore, the estimated user embeddings are very close to the true private user embeddings, which showcases the risk of leaking private user embeddings.
For FNCF, while both the original and modified RAIFLE have excellent AUC, the latter slightly outperforms the former, which is corroborated by our K-S test with a p-value of ≪0.01much-less-thanabsent0.01\ll 0.01.
The estimated user embeddings in this case have much higher error compared to the estimations in FCF.
Optimizing with both the model parameters and the public item embeddings does not appear to help.

references: Table 8 shows the average simulated utility of the learning-to-rank models (Section 4.1.3) for different levels of LDP budget ε𝜀\varepsilon (δ=10−8𝛿superscript108\delta=10^{-8}) on the MSLR-WEB10K dataset. The models are trained on a single pass of the train portion in Fold 1 of the dataset, where every user is assigned one unique query to ensure that no query is trained on more than once. FL aggregation occurs for every 100 users. We measure the normalized discounted cumulative gain for the top 10 items (NDCG@10) on the corresponding test portion. The simulation is repeated 10 times with different aggregation order and initial model parameters.
